We start by identifying the quick assets as those current assets that are most liquid. The quick assets include:

• Cash on Hand: 2,105,753.37  
• Bank Deposits: 559,055.66  
• Interest Receivable: 6,494.02  
• Accounts Receivable: 335,639.38  

Step 1: Sum the quick assets  
  Quick Assets = 2,105,753.37 + 559,055.66 + 6,494.02 + 335,639.38  
  Quick Assets = 3,006,942.43

Step 2: Identify the current liabilities at the end date  
  Total Current Liabilities = 5,637,910.70

Step 3: Calculate the Quick Ratio  
  Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Total Current Liabilities  
  Quick Ratio = 3,006,942.43 / 5,637,910.70 ≈ 0.533

Rounded to two decimal places, the Quick Ratio is 0.53.

Thus, the solution is:
